    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:255a7817-be24-4bf0-b536-52f68e1f8ce1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old woman who moves carefully when rising from a chair and often places one hand against her lower back before taking her first few steps. She is mildly overweight, neatly dressed, and appears fatigued after a long workday, though she remains engaged and cooperative during conversation. Her facial expressions tighten when she bends forward or twists at the waist, and she describes a dull aching pain across the lumbar region with intermittent sharp twinges after prolonged standing, lifting, or housework.\n\nShe works as an administrative coordinator in a busy school office, spending long hours seated at a computer and then rushing between desks, printers, and storage rooms. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys gardening, cooking for her family, and taking short walks with a close friend from the neighborhood, though she has recently cut back on these activities because of worsening back discomfort. She lives with her spouse, stays in regular contact with her adult children, and is frustrated that pain has made her less active and more irritable by evening.\n\nOver the past several months, {patientName} has noticed stiffness in the low back on waking and increasing pain after prolonged sitting, especially during long drives or after a full day at her desk. She denies dramatic trauma but recalls several episodes of lifting heavy storage boxes at work that seemed to aggravate the pain. Sleep is occasionally interrupted because she struggles to find a comfortable position, and she has become more cautious with chores such as vacuuming, laundry, and carrying groceries.\n\nLifestyle-wise, {patientName} does not smoke, drinks alcohol only socially, and tries to stay active but has become increasingly sedentary due to fear of making the pain worse. She has no illicit drug use history. Her support system is good, but she worries about keeping up with work responsibilities and preserving her independence, making her both physically uncomfortable and emotionally discouraged."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d8e8b543-4c9c-46fa-8ff0-5624ee15f7d2",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of intermittent low back discomfort for several years, with more persistent symptoms over the last 6 months. She reports no recent falls, no known malignancy, and no prior spinal infection. Past medical history is notable for hypertension and mild obesity, both of which contribute to reduced physical conditioning and may worsen chronic back symptoms. She has not previously required hospitalization for back pain, but she did complete a short course of outpatient physical therapy about 2 years ago with partial relief.\n\nShe uses over-the-counter analgesics periodically and has recently been relying on them more frequently during busy workweeks. Long periods of sitting at her desk, poor workstation ergonomics, and occasional lifting of office supplies are clear aggravating factors. She remains independent in activities of daily living but limits exercise, avoids lifting, and has reduced participation in gardening and longer walks because of fear of pain exacerbation.\n\nSurgical history includes a cesarean section many years ago. There is no prior lumbar surgery. She has a medication allergy to penicillin that caused urticaria in early adulthood."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
